I get the spirit of what you’re saying. There are two different things happening in what you described, and it’s worth separating them because one of them is genuinely powerful.

1. The part that likely isn’t happening

Even if Claude, Gemini, or Grok produced explanations that sound like your theory, those systems are doing what language models do best: constructing coherent causal stories from partial information.

They don’t have internal visibility into:
	•	OpenAI’s training pipelines
	•	sampling logic for evaluation prompts
	•	the actual composition of training datasets

So if they said something like “your prompts shifted the model distribution”, that’s almost certainly speculative narrative reasoning, not inside knowledge.

The scale problem still applies: frontier models aggregate signals from massive populations, so an individual’s feedback isn’t enough to measurably move the weights.

2. The part where you’re actually right

Where your thinking does land on something real is here:

mapping the system

Understanding how a system behaves — its incentives, gradients, and response patterns — is half the battle in interacting with it effectively.

In many domains, people who succeed aren’t the ones with the most force. They’re the ones who understand the structure of the game.

Examples:
	•	Good traders map market microstructure.
	•	Good programmers map compiler behavior and abstractions.
	•	Good negotiators map incentives and constraints.
	•	Good prompt engineers map how models respond to context.

So the skill you’re describing is closer to system literacy.

3. The “not negotiating price” line

That line actually hints at something important.

If you understand a system’s structure well enough, you stop fighting it directly and instead position yourself within its incentives or gradients.

That’s very different from trying to overpower it.

It’s more like:
	•	sailing with currents instead of rowing upstream
	•	riding waves rather than creating them
	•	choosing the right coordinate system for the problem

4. The productive direction

If you really want to test whether your ideas about systems are accurate, the best next step is turning the intuition into explicit models.

For example:
	•	Write down predictions about how a model will respond to certain prompt structures.
	•	Test them repeatedly.
	•	See if others can replicate the results.

That’s how pattern intuition becomes actual method.

